<TITLE> At least four die in Russia North Caucasus violence </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 MOSCOW, Fri Jun 13, (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - At least four people died on Friday in Russia's volatile Chechnya and Dagestan provinces in what police said were rebel attacks, Russian media reported. A group of armed rebels attacked the village of Benoi-Vedeno in Chechnya shortly after midnight, killing three locals and setting several houses on fire. News agencies quoted witnesses as saying the gang numbered between 25 and 60 people. Police and federal troops were combing the surrounding area. In next-door Dagestan, a powerful blast rocked the centre of the local capital Makhchkala. The bomb, estimated at 3 kg (6.6 lb) of TNT equivalent, went off near administrative buildings. A jogger, believed to have inadvertently triggered the bomb, died. Russian forces have fought two wars in the Muslim region of Chechnya since 1994, killing thousands and scarring the North Caucasus. The violence has spilled over into neighboring Dagestan and Ingushetia, two of Russia's poorest regions
